    },
    {
      "id": "16I4H7hIDDo-toZJO-Wn_",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 409.1455823097121,
      "y": 867.3340559656401,
      "width": 1368.3790283203125,
      "height": 1875,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "aX",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 491494727,
      "version": 3192,
      "versionNonce": 1255598281,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1765997854473,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Approach to bronze to silver\n- Read the last watermark to only pull new changes.  This is where CDF can help\n- Pull only changed rows from bronze \n- cleanse and shape into silver\n- deduplicate the change set (latest change wins per key)\n     - This is where there are multiple change events for the same key in one run, MERGE should see one row per (business_key, visit_date)\nw = Window.partitionBy('business_key', 'visit_date').orderBy(\n    F.col('source_updated_at').desc_nulls_last(),\n    F.col('ingest_ts').desc_nulls_last()\n)\n\nstaged_dedup = (\n    staged.withColumn('rn', F.row_number().over(w))\n        .filter(F.col('rn) == 1)\n        .drop('rn')\n)\n\n- The above pattern is doing \"latest wins deduplication\" on your change set before you MERGE into silver\n    - The window piece is defining a window equal to groups + ranking rules\n    - partitionBy business key and visit date is treating all rows that share the same (business_key, visit_date) as one group\n    - order by desc_nulls_last means sort rows so the most recent change comes first\n        - first by source_updated_at (the best indicator of \"real\" recency from the source system\n        - if that's tied or null, break ties by ingest_ts (when your pipeline landed it)\n    - Assign a row number within each group\n        - This is done by staged.withColumns('rn', F.row_number().over(w))\n        - row_number() gives 1,2,3,... within each (business_key, visit_date) group in that sorted order\n        - The newest row in each group gets rn = 1\n    - Keep only the newest row per key\n        - .filter(F.col('rn')==1).drop('rn')\n            - This filters to exactly one row per (business_key, visit_date): the \"winner\"\n            - Then removes the helper column\n            - Result:  staged_dedup has no duplicate keys, and each key maps to the single most up-to-date record you want to apply\n\n\nUpdated Latest Wins code for using CDF:\nfrom pyspark.sql. import functions as F\nfrom pyspark.sql.window import Window\n\ncdf = (spark.read\n    .option('readChangeFeed', 'true')\n    .option('startingVersion', start_version)\n    .table('lakehouse.silver_patient_visits')\n)\n\n# keep only the rows that represent the final state you want to apply downstream\ncdf_effective = cdf.filter(\n    F.col('_change_type').isin('insert', 'update_postimage', 'delete')\n)\n\nw = Window.partitionBy('business_key', 'visit_date').orderBy(\n    F.col('_commit_version').desc(),\n    F.col('_commit_timestamp').desc()\n)\n\nlatest_per_key = (cdf_effective\n    .withColumn('rn', F.row_number().over(w))\n    .filter('rn = 1')\n    .drop('rn')\n)\n\n- Then downstream, typically:\n        - delete when _change_type = 'delete'\n        - upsert for insert and update_postimage\n\n\n- reduce work using your \"recent date\" skew (optional but high value)\n    - Because your updates cluster around recent visit_date, you can compute a min/max date window and let the \n      MERGE condition include it (helps pruning/skipping)\n        date_bounds = staged_dedup.select(\n            F.min('visit_date').alias('min_d'),\n            F.max('visit_date').alias('max_d')        \n        ).collect()[0]\n        \n        min_d = date_bounds['min_d']\n        max_d = date_bounds['max_d']",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Approach to bronze to silver\n- Read the last watermark to only pull new changes.  This is where CDF can help\n- Pull only changed rows from bronze \n- cleanse and shape into silver\n- deduplicate the change set (latest change wins per key)\n     - This is where there are multiple change events for the same key in one run, MERGE should see one row per (business_key, visit_date)\nw = Window.partitionBy('business_key', 'visit_date').orderBy(\n    F.col('source_updated_at').desc_nulls_last(),\n    F.col('ingest_ts').desc_nulls_last()\n)\n\nstaged_dedup = (\n    staged.withColumn('rn', F.row_number().over(w))\n        .filter(F.col('rn) == 1)\n        .drop('rn')\n)\n\n- The above pattern is doing \"latest wins deduplication\" on your change set before you MERGE into silver\n    - The window piece is defining a window equal to groups + ranking rules\n    - partitionBy business key and visit date is treating all rows that share the same (business_key, visit_date) as one group\n    - order by desc_nulls_last means sort rows so the most recent change comes first\n        - first by source_updated_at (the best indicator of \"real\" recency from the source system\n        - if that's tied or null, break ties by ingest_ts (when your pipeline landed it)\n    - Assign a row number within each group\n        - This is done by staged.withColumns('rn', F.row_number().over(w))\n        - row_number() gives 1,2,3,... within each (business_key, visit_date) group in that sorted order\n        - The newest row in each group gets rn = 1\n    - Keep only the newest row per key\n        - .filter(F.col('rn')==1).drop('rn')\n            - This filters to exactly one row per (business_key, visit_date): the \"winner\"\n            - Then removes the helper column\n            - Result:  staged_dedup has no duplicate keys, and each key maps to the single most up-to-date record you want to apply\n\n\nUpdated Latest Wins code for using CDF:\nfrom pyspark.sql. import functions as F\nfrom pyspark.sql.window import Window\n\ncdf = (spark.read\n    .option('readChangeFeed', 'true')\n    .option('startingVersion', start_version)\n    .table('lakehouse.silver_patient_visits')\n)\n\n# keep only the rows that represent the final state you want to apply downstream\ncdf_effective = cdf.filter(\n    F.col('_change_type').isin('insert', 'update_postimage', 'delete')\n)\n\nw = Window.partitionBy('business_key', 'visit_date').orderBy(\n    F.col('_commit_version').desc(),\n    F.col('_commit_timestamp').desc()\n)\n\nlatest_per_key = (cdf_effective\n    .withColumn('rn', F.row_number().over(w))\n    .filter('rn = 1')\n    .drop('rn')\n)\n\n- Then downstream, typically:\n        - delete when _change_type = 'delete'\n        - upsert for insert and update_postimage\n\n\n- reduce work using your \"recent date\" skew (optional but high value)\n    - Because your updates cluster around recent visit_date, you can compute a min/max date window and let the \n      MERGE condition include it (helps pruning/skipping)\n        date_bounds = staged_dedup.select(\n            F.min('visit_date').alias('min_d'),\n            F.max('visit_date').alias('max_d')        \n        ).collect()[0]\n        \n        min_d = date_bounds['min_d']\n        max_d = date_bounds['max_d']",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "MWclbedc8vC1aU-L2zBjy",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1287.2269160567193,
